Well, that and some symptom divergence.

card: {'url': 'https://www.mediamatters.org/rumble/rumble-profiting-creators-who-spread-antisemitism', 'title': 'Rumble is profiting from creators who spread antisemitism', 'description': 'Rumble ‚Äî the right-wing video-streaming site that markets itself as a ‚Äúfree speech‚Äù YouTube competitor ‚Äî is profiting from advertisements on content from far-right figures and groups who have histories of spreading antisemitism and conspiracy theories about Jewish people. Rumble has teamed up with the Republican National Committee to exclusively stream GOP presidential primary debates.\xa0 Additionally, Rumble has previously allowed white nationalists to profit from its platform and has profited itself from pre-roll advertisements on videos from QAnon conspiracy theorists, white nationalists, and other extremists.\xa0 Based on a Media Matters review, pre-roll ads are running before videos from at least 16 Rumble accounts of far-right figures and groups who have spread antisemitism. Some of the figures associated with these Rumble accounts have promoted white nationalist, neo-Nazi, and extremist ideologies.\xa0 Rumble has its\xa0own\xa0ad platform, which\xa0allows advertisers\xa0to place pre-roll videos and display ads on the video-streaming platform and\xa0boasts\xa0Truth Social as a publisher, but a majority of ads on Rumble\xa0reportedly\xa0come from Google‚Äôs ad network. This means that Google\xa0is\xa0monetizing\xa0and driving new users and traffic to Rumble ‚Äî ultimately\xa0assisting\xa0the website to make money as a\xa0cesspool\xa0of\xa0extremist\xa0conspiracy theories\xa0and a\xa0safe\xa0haven\xa0for users banned from mainstream social media sites.', 'language': 'en', 'type': 'link', 'author_name': '', 'author_url': '', 'provider_name': 'Media Matters for America', 'provider_url': '', 'html': '', 'width': 1024, 'height': 600, 'image': 'https://storage.googleapis.com/hci-social-storage/cache/preview_cards/images/002/411/073/original/68a50021f16f43e0.png', 'image_description': '', 'embed_url': '', 'blurhash': 'UQ9tu[WUDiof8^jb%MbHx^j[RjaeRPj[t8ay', 'published_at': None}

content:
Old dead github project with ~70mb of assets in LFS in it started getting mass downloaded rapidly last week blowing through my LFS bandwidth limits.

Lesson learned, no LFS in public repos but what's really concerning is that it took #github 5 days to respond to my support ticket about this.

content:
Well I woke up at 6 am because I really had to pee (as manifested by a dream of peeing for a long time in a toilet that people kept barging into) and had serious brain gerbils about this whole manifesto-syllabus, including a long argument about why I think it's important to read it, along the lines of my "Must We Read de Sade?" series https://rinsemiddlebliss.com/posts/2017-02-01-angry-about-literature-must-we-read-de-sade-part-1/

But also similar to why I thought it was so important for me to read Derrida's *Of Grammatology* to crassly quote my own self

"I think it‚Äôs important to read books whose influence has permeated your discipline so that you know where the ideas came from."

https://rinsemiddlebliss.com/posts/2023-03-17-of-grammatology-derrida-review/

And just, in general, I think it's useful to read primary texts that influence the secondary texts you're reading about.

content:
I‚Äôm going to miss going through ‚ÄúHear My Sad Story.‚Äù Each chapter covers a different song, and the book is arranged thematically: disasters, martyrs, labor, etc. Polenberg is clearly a lefty, and several themes emerge like racial injustice, corrupt policing, the collusion of government and business. The only weakness is ‚ÄúHouse of the Rising Sun‚Äù which misses an opportunity to talk about the lives of New Orleans prostitutes. Overall it‚Äôs a mighty fine read for #FolkMusic fans.

content:
Two years ago, we worked on this fun project that allowed 2 friends wearing AR headsets to capture a physical object and virtually drop it at a specific location in their partner's home. Going back and forth, sending "thinking of you" objects or clues throughout the day.

Learn more at @yyteng and Joanne Leong's presentation at #CSCW2023 tomorrow Wed at 9am at Great Lakes A2 or check out their blog post: https://medium.com/acm-cscw/social-wormholes-using-an-ecosystem-of-connected-things-to-connect-people-f45ac924b574

This is the last paper from our former HCI team at Snap!

I realize there are some brands that are more evaded than others.

And I'm not meaning to tell folks who have had false negatives that their experiences didn't happen.

Just ... it's not some big pharma lie that the tests can still work. They can. But they might work differently--and eventually maybe differently enough that they're no longer an effective early warning system.

Afaik we are not at that dire point yet.

content:
Toward the Decipherment of Harappan (2022)
----
- 9 hours ago | 5 points | 0 comments
- URL: https://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=53609
- Discussions: https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=37910923
- Summary: Computer scientists are using machine learning algorithms to attempt to decipher the Harappan script, an ancient language that has remained undeciphered for over 100 years. Previous attempts to decode the script have been controversial, with some researchers suggesting the symbols are purely decorative rather than a true script. By applying machine learning to analyze patterns in how languages change over time, researchers hope to uncover the meaning behind the symbols. However, there are challenges in using AI for decipherment, including the limited data available and the complexity of understanding cultural symbolism.
